  "prompt": "What is the difference between earned and unearned income?",
  "response": "Earned income and unearned income are two different types of income that individuals can receive. Here's the difference between them:\n\n**Earned Income:**\n1. **Definition:** Earned income is the money you receive from working or providing services. It typically involves active participation or effort.\n2. **Examples:** \n   - Salaries and wages from employment.\n   - Tips and commissions.\n   - Income from self-employment or freelance work.\n   - Bonuses and other financial incentives related to work.\n\n**Unearned Income:**\n1. **Definition:** Unearned income is the money you receive from sources other than active employment or services you provide. It generally involves passive income sources.\n2. **Examples:** \n   - Interest from savings accounts, bonds, or other investments.\n   - Dividends received from stocks.\n   - Rental income from property.\n   - Social Security benefits.\n   - Pensions and annuities.\n   - Capital gains from the sale of investments or property.\n   - Alimony and child support (depending on jurisdiction, as they may be classified differently in some cases).\n\n**Key Differences:**\n- **Effort:** Earned income requires active effort, such as working a job or running a business, whereas unearned income typically requires minimal ongoing effort after the initial investment or setup.\n- **Tax Treatment:** In many jurisdictions, the tax rates on earned and unearned income can differ. For example, unearned income from investments may be taxed at different rates than wages or salaries.\n- **Source:** Earned income directly comes from your labor, while unearned income comes from investments, inheritance, or passive activities.\n\nUnderstanding the distinction between earned and unearned income is important for tax purposes and for personal financial planning.",
